    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Just Another Bric-a-Brac on the Wall</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By JAMIE WALLIS</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Photos of rooms that college students have decorated using old album covers or actual vinyl records (special section, Education Life)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>STUDENTS have always pilfered from parents' closets and scoured thrift stores for the latest looks. So it's not surprising that as music marches into the digital domain, they're repurposing audio antiques as art. Urban Outfitters, which sells LP frames for $15, notes an uptick in sales. ''As we get further away from the LP as mass-media vehicle, they are becoming more collectible,'' says Greg Lehmkuhl, a product development director. Are VHS mobiles far behind?</p>
        <p>JAMIE WALLIS</p>
      </block>
